SIMPLE: smite
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Smite
<hw>Smite</hw> <pr>(sm⟦imac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Smote</conjf> <pr>(sm⟦omac⟧t)</pr>,
rarely <conjf>Smit</conjf> <pr>(sm⟦icr⟧t)</pr>; <pos>p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Smitten</conjf> <pr>(sm⟦icr⟧t"t'n)</pr>, rarely
<conjf>Smit</conjf>, or <conjf>Smote</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Smiting</conjf> <pr>(sm⟦imac⟧t"⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS.
<ets>sm⟦imac⟧tan</ets> to smite, to soil, pollute; akin to OFries.
<ets>sm⟦imac⟧ta</ets> to smite, LG. <ets>smiten</ets>, D.
<ets>smijten</ets>, G. <ets>schmeissen</ets>, OHG.
<ets>sm⟦imac⟧zan</ets> to smear, stroke, OSw. & dial. Sw.
<ets>smita</ets> to smite, Dan. <ets>smide</ets> to throw, Goth.
bi<ets>smeitan</ets>, to anoint, besmear; cf. Skr. <ets>m⟦emac⟧d</ets>
to be fat. The original sense seems to have been, to daub on, to smear.
Cf. <er>Smut</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To strike; to inflict a blow
upon with the hand, or with any instrument held in the hand, or with a
missile thrown by the hand; <as>as, to <ex>smite</ex> with the fist,
with a rod, sword, spear, or stone</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whosoever shall <qex>smite</qex> thee on thy right cheek, turn to
him the other also.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. v. 39.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And David . . . took thence a stone, and slang it, and
<qex>smote</qex> the Philistine in his forehead.</q> <rj><qau>1 Sam.
xvii. 49.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cause to strike; to use as an instrument in
striking or hurling.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Prophesy, and <qex>smite</qex> thine hands together.</q>
<rj><qau>Ezek. xxi. 14.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Saul . . . <qex>smote</qex> the javelin into the wall.</q>
<rj><qau>1 Sam. xix. 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To destroy the life of by beating, or by weapons of
any kind; to slay by a blow; to kill; <as>as, to <ex>smite</ex> one with
the sword, or with an arrow or other instrument</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To put to rout in battle; to overthrow by
war.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To blast; to destroy the life or vigor of, as by a
stroke or by some visitation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The flax and the barly was <qex>smitten</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ex.
ix. 31.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To afflict; to chasten; to punish.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let us not mistake God's goodness, nor imagine, because he
<qex>smites</qex> us, that we are forsaken by him.</q>
<rj><qau>Wake.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To strike or affect with passion, as love or
fear.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The charms that <qex>smite</qex> the simple heart.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Smit</qex> with the love of sister arts we came.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To smite off</b></col>, <cd>to cut off.</cd> --
<col><b>To smite out</b></col>, <cd>to knock out, as a tooth.</cd>
<au>Exod. xxi. 27.</au> -- <col><b>To smite with the tongue</b></col>,
<cd>to reproach or upbraid; to revile.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Jer. xviii. 18.</au></rj> </cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smite</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Smite
<hw>Smite</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To strike; to collide; to
beat.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The heart melteth, and the knees smite together.</q> <rj><qau>Nah.
ii. 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smite</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Smite
<hw>Smite</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of smiting; a blow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smiter</ent>⟦br⟧
